        'en' => <<<'HTML'
<h2>Origins in the San Pedro neighbourhood (1982–1983)</h2>
<figure class="historia-foto">
<img src="/assets/img/historia/decada-1980.jpg" alt="Urban setting, archival black and white photo" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
<figcaption>Archival image. The brotherhood grew from dialogue between neighbours, local business and the parish in a quarter that sought stronger community and social support.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>This page summarises the chronicle and minutes that tell how the brotherhood was born around <strong>San Pedro parish</strong>. The seed appears in Santa Isabel street, but in <strong>Martín Franco’s jeweller’s shop</strong> on San Pedro street (<strong>1982</strong>) the idea of a neighbourhood cofradía takes shape. Manuel Guerrero, Father <strong>Galindo</strong> and José Serván discuss neglect and social need, inspired by other improvement projects. The parish priest demands bringing <strong>neighbours closer to the Church</strong>. Meetings produce a committed group —including María del Carmen Rubira, Martín Franco, Antonio Rubira Urbano, José Serván, Pedro Olmo Morales, Francisco Trujillo and Manuel Guerrero— and a team of 22 people with religious, social and cultural aims.</p>
<p>On <strong>Holy Thursday 1983</strong> the Lord of Gran Poder was to visit for the parish passion play; a broken stretcher prevented entry, yet the decorated barrio kept the desire for its own procession. After Holy Saturday talks with Father Galindo, on <strong>4 April 1983</strong> Manuel Guerrero Sigler’s manuscript fixes founding bases with the parish priest and founders. The <strong>Gabaldón family</strong> deposits a sorrowful Virgin; the title moves toward <strong>Jesus del Perdón</strong> and a Marian dedication, with diocesan approval on <strong>3 June 1983</strong>. A managing board is formed, quotas begin, 10,000 holy cards are printed, and the parish council sets strict penitential rules for the first outing: night procession, Rosary, no music, austerity.</p>
<h2>First cult, cultural week and commissioning the Lord (1983–1985)</h2>
<figure class="historia-foto">
<img src="/assets/img/historia/parroquia-barrio.jpg" alt="Church and streets, archival photo" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
<figcaption>Archival image. Worship, solidarity and street procession remain the three poles of brotherhood life.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>The first <strong>cultural week</strong> (October 1983) includes Bishop <strong>Antonio Dorado Soto</strong>; the <strong>Dolorosa de San Pedro</strong> is blessed; a blue velvet mantle with gold lace is made. On <strong>15 September 1983</strong> she processes at dawn. In 1984 brothers vote for <strong>Manuel Hernández León’s</strong> model for <strong>Christ of Mercy in his third fall</strong> with Veronica and Simon; contracts and neighbourhood fundraising follow. The young group drives social work (over <strong>70&nbsp;% of spending</strong>). On <strong>23 March 1985</strong> the image is blessed; on <strong>2 April 1985</strong>, Holy Thursday, the first penitential procession sets out with cream tunics, purple masks, esparto belts, a rough guide cross and drums only — and rain. The brotherhood issues its <strong>first Holy Week poster</strong> and sends statutes to the diocese; the pro-cult board is authorised in July 1985.</p>
<h2>Statutes, float, growth (1986–1993)</h2>
<figure class="historia-foto">
<img src="/assets/img/historia/procesion.jpg" alt="Procession, archival black and white" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
<figcaption>Archival image. Penitential station knits devotion, discipline and shared memory.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>Decrees approve statutes in 1986; the <strong>costaleros’ guild</strong> is founded. The diocese questions the Holy Thursday slot; a heavy new <strong>mystery float by Francisco Bailac</strong> fits the church doorway. In 1989 the brotherhood reaches the patroness church and official route; the <strong>shield</strong> is renewed (oval, crown of thorns and shroud); <strong>corporate medals</strong> arrive in 1990. Devotion to <strong>Our Lady of Health</strong> grows with a women’s carrying team, new platforms and later the palio. Decrees in 1990 and 1996 widen women’s rights, including governance. In <strong>1994</strong> the brotherhood supplies the official Holy Week poster painted by <strong>Pepe Gallego</strong> from photographs by Gabriel Solís Carvajal.</p>
<h2>Embroidery workshop, palio, house and trials (1994–1999)</h2>
<p>The <strong>embroidery workshop</strong> led by Antonia Gil, monthly brotherhood Masses, new Nazarene tunics and <strong>Ramón León Peñuelas’s</strong> palio design mark the late 1990s. In <strong>1998</strong> Our Lady processes under canopy despite heavy rain; work begins on the <strong>brotherhood house</strong>. After a parish change in 1998, <strong>1999</strong> brings internal crisis, diocesan intervention and a <strong>stewardship board</strong> under Carlos Granja with deacon Lucio Victorino Osta; nonetheless the <strong>Holy Thursday 1999</strong> procession still takes place along a long official route. Later years restore stability, bulletins and devotion; Our Lady of Health continues her rosary through San Pedro.</p>
<h2>Closing</h2>
<figure class="historia-foto">
<img src="/assets/img/historia/hermandad-hoy.jpg" alt="Community, archival image" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
<figcaption>Archival image. Today the brotherhood continues the same calling: faith, service to the neighbourhood and handing tradition on.</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>From the jeweller’s shop to Sevilla journeys, first cream and purple habits, posters, palio, embroidery, shield and medals, the story is decades of often anonymous work: brothers, bearers, chaplains, sculptors, musicians and families who paid dues and raffle tickets. This web summary condenses the book of history; full dates, figures and minutes belong in the corporation’s official archive and publications.</p>
